<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="1">
[[ Genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C4304186-4FD4-4672-BDF1-AC51D2C01419" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Glyptothorax Blyth 1860:154" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Glyptothorax Blyth</taxonomicName>
]]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C4304186-4FD4-4672-BDF1-AC51D2C01419" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Glyptothorax Blyth 1860:154" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Glyptothorax Blyth, 1860</taxonomicName>
is a diverse (84 nominal species), widely distributed genus of sisorid catfish known from Asia Minor (in the Tigris and Euphrates River drainages) east- and southwards to the Yangtze River drainage and southeast Asia. Members of the genus are diagnosed in having a thoracic adhesive apparatus comprising an elliptical field of folded longitudinal pleats of skin, a detached distal portion of the premaxilla, and long and thin lateral arms of the vomer that extend under the entire length of the articular process of the lateral ethmoid (de Pinna, 1996). The genus is very diverse in the Indian subcontinent (29 of the 84 nominal species are known from there), although the taxonomy of Indian 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C4304186-4FD4-4672-BDF1-AC51D2C01419" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Glyptothorax Blyth 1860:154" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Glyptothorax</taxonomicName>
is poorly understood.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="2">
During recent ichthyological surveys of northeast India, two species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C4304186-4FD4-4672-BDF1-AC51D2C01419" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Glyptothorax Blyth 1860:154" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Glyptothorax</taxonomicName>
were obtained from the Ganges River drainage. One of the species was referable to 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="telchitta">G. telchitta (Hamilton, 1822)</taxonomicName>
, but the second morphologically similar species was not readily identifiable. Further investigation revealed that the second species is referable to 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="botius">G. botius (Hamilton, 1822)</taxonomicName>
, and that the identities of the two species have been confused for some time. The objective of this study is to clarify the identities of these two species and to redescribe them. Neotypes are also designated for 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F2EC45B7-1BB6-44B8-8961-D9A43F991DDE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pimelodus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pimelodus telchitta Hamilton 1822:185, 378" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="telchitta">Pimelodus telchitta Hamilton, 1822</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:39B07C09-5C32-47B8-A3A0-2C8124D11CC1" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Pimelodus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pimelodus botius Hamilton 1822:192, 378" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="botius">Pimelodus botius Hamilton, 1822</taxonomicName>
to fix the taxonomy of these species.
</paragraph>
